Just obtained my latest kidney results and received another big blow. The results are as follows:

eGFR 35
Serum creatinine - 150 umol/L
Urea - 13.9 mmol
Hg - 9.4 (severely anemic!)
HbA1c - 9.0
Protein/Creatinine Ratio - 80.0 mg/mmol (normal is less than 10)
PTH - 14.9 pmol/L (ref 1.6-6.9)
1.25 Dihydroxycalciferol - 85 pmol/L (60-208)
Vit D - 58 (51-140)

Potassium, calcium, phosphate and all other values are normal. 

Urine culture shows "mixed growth of bowel and/or perineal flora, including yeasts. While predominant pathogen has not been identified, uti has not been excluded". Looks like I have another bout of a UTI. 

I've got to work on my blood sugar control! I know my numbers have been all over the place. My diabetic control has become very erratic and difficult. I just don't know what to do. 

I feel devastated. Perhaps the first thing to do is take care of my will.



Some new things my Neph has informed me of about caring for people with CKD.

1. Anemia is not a threat to kidney health as once believed. The body does adjust to new lowered levels of Hg in the body apparently. 

2. EPO injections such as Aranesp do pose a risk to cardiovascular health & should be given with caution on an ongoing basis.

3. Severe low protein diets in fact do very little to preserve or halt CKD progression and cause other serious health problems longer term. Nephrologists are increasingly abandoning low protein diets for CKD patients.

4. CKD is a very complex & often baffling condition that Nephrologists struggle to deal with (which often explains the looks of depression I've often witnessed on a many a face of a Neph).

5. Neph just don't have the answers & no one else seems to have them either. This explains the funereal undertaker-like atmosphere of Renal Depts in hospitals.

6. The public has caught on that kidney disease is like what leprosy was in biblical times! A social worker today for example, had the same look of dark depression when I told her what disease I am battling with.

7. A kidney patient is alone in their battle to find whatever joy, optimism and psychological well-being they can hang onto. Nephs are often astounded when they witness this in a kidney patient.

8. When the chips are down & an adverse medical event occurs, Nephs are inaccessible & one is left to survive in ER on their own. ER depts have in fact a very basic understanding of CKD at best. 



There is no simple answer. There are so many variables in each person and each dialysis modality and prescription. This is an interesting article on clearances of solutes.


A sad but forgotten truth: the story of slow-moving solutes in fast hemodialysis.

Eloot S1, Van Biesen W, Vanholder R.

Author information 

Abstract

When trying to optimize hemodialysis adequacy, it can be questioned whether one should focus on the dialyzer or on the patient. Another crucial question is whether the currently applied dialysis adequacy parameter, Kt/V(urea) , is a reliable marker. For the small and water-soluble solutes, recent advances in convective strategies and/or new dialyzer designs do not add much removal capacity. Depending on their specific kinetics, generally quite different from those of urea, small solute removal benefits from longer or more frequent dialysis. Clearance of beta-2-microglobulin ((2) M), a marker of middle molecule removal pattern, is improved with dialysis using more open and permselective membranes, as well as by using high convective volume strategies. Furthermore, longer and more frequent dialyses have highly favorable removal characteristics because they facilitate the retarded transport between plasmatic and extraplasmatic compartments over which these molecules are distributed. As (2) M may not be representative of other middle molecules, future kinetic analyses of alternative middle molecules will be of the utmost interest. Protein-bound solute clearance is improved by convective techniques, but not by more open dialyzer pores. Knowledge of their kinetics should be helpful in interpreting the observation that frequent (but not longer) dialysis enhances protein-bound solute removal. Hence, further technical improvements in dialyzers will have only a minor impact on dialysis adequacy, as retarded solute movement in the patient plays a decisive role. As urea kinetics is not representative of the kinetics of protein-bound compounds, middle molecules, nor even of other small and water-soluble solutes, it becomes self-evident that urea clearance is a poor predictor of many aspects of dialysis adequacy.
